 style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> refers to our hidden variable and represents our estimated precitor variable</li>\n<li>\n<p>Where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>H</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">H</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08125em;\">H</span></span></span></span> represents the state transition matrix</p>\n<ul>\n<li>These could be made up of the beta coefficients for a linear regression model, or the autoregressive coefficients in an AR (or ARIMA) model, etc.</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li>Where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>ϵ</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\epsilon_{i}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.58056em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϵ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> represents the error term for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>y</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">y_{i}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.19444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.31166399999999994em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.03588em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">i</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Advantages of the Kalman Filter</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>The Kalman filter is predictive and adaptive, since it looks forward with an estimate of the covariance and mean of the time series of one step into the future</li>\n<li>The Kalman filter does not require stationary data (neural networks usually do)</li>\n<li>It has a smooth representation of the series, while not requiring knowledge of the future</li>\n<li>A potential disadvantage of the Kalman filter is that it typically assumes linearity</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>References</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://bilgin.esme.org/BitsAndBytes/KalmanFilterforDummies\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Kalman Filter for Dummies</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.r-bloggers.com/the-kalman-filter-for-financial-time-series/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Example of using Kalman Filter</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.cs.cmu.edu/~guestrin/Class/10701-S05/slides/hmms.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Kalman Filters and Hidden Markov Models</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CaCcOwJPytQ\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Lecture on Kalman Filters</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://faculty.washington.edu/ezivot/econ584/notes/statespacemodels.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">State Space Models and the Kalman Filter</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://biorobotics.ri.cmu.edu/papers/sbp_papers/integrated3/kleeman_kalman_basics.pdf\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow\">Understanding and Applying the Kalman Filter</a></li>\n</ul>"}},"pageContext":{"slug":"ml/bayesian_inference/kalman_filter","previousSlug":"ml/bayesian_inference/mcmc","nextSlug":null,"previousTitle":"MCMC Methods","nextTitle":null}},"staticQueryHashes":[]}